Observation Details: In case Steve Hampton or Art Reisman see this: STALLCUP'S LAW HAS NOT BEEN VIOLATED. I came upon two flocks. One flew single-file (Bushtits...Tusken Raiders...) across Baseline Rd., and it numbered a tidy 17 individuals. The other drifted aimlessly about the indigenous plantings near The Shack; at one point, the birds went across the trail, and I quickly got on 13.  OMG THIS IS A PROOF OF THE GOLDBACH CONJECTURE!!!! As to the pics below, the male (by eye color) is from the flock at The Shack; the female (also by eye color) is from the flock that crossed Baseline Rd. Hilarious to watch as each one would get out of the way of traffic. By the way, the female is banded. How cool is that. Oak Thorne's handiwork, no doubt.  Two audio recordings, too, of the Bushtit vocalization that I believe functions as song. First is a series from a single individual (male by eye color); the second is a single bout of song that I pulled out of a longer recording of Black-capped Chickadees (pulled from MLML614320454).

Observation Details: A flock bopped around the Greenlee/Waneka buffer for quite some time, then raided the Greenlee feeders. Flock size in such situations quite difficult to work out—despite lengthy period of observation (at least 20 minutes). When birds crossed the little clearings in the buffer and and at the feeder, I could get quickly on 20+, with at least 5 still hanging back. 25 likely an undercount.  Media:  ML612768147: typical adult female (by eye color). ML612768151: birds at millet feeder, and note band on one of the females (by eye color). ML612768156: part of the flock at suet feeder. ML612768161: part of the flock at millet feeder. ML612768166: The flock raids the Greenlee feeders. ML612768172: The flock at sundown in the Greenlee/Waneka buffer. Note the "Brownian motion," entirely typical. ML612768173: A single male (by eye color) feeding, with diverse vocalizations by flockmates.  Photo/video editing. Videos: slight stabilization for ML612768161 and ML612768173; wasn't necessary for ML612768172. For photos, the intense red/orange/yellow (higher wavelengths) is true/natural, given the low sun angle and surrounding vegetation; all images sharpened (because of low light conditions ).

Media notes: This is the same nest photographed March 2, 2017. At that time, Bushtits were adding material to the nest. This nest is unusual for the species in that it somewhat resembles an oriole nest. However, the small side entrance can be seen along with the small pieces of vegetation ornamenting the entrance, typical for Bushtits. Either the Bushtits build their nest into an old oriole nest, or the branch structure of the cottonwood favored building a bulkier nest than is typical of Bushtits.

Observation Details: In case Steve Hampton or Art Reisman see this: STALLCUP'S LAW HAS NOT BEEN VIOLATED. I came upon two flocks. One flew single-file (Bushtits...Tusken Raiders...) across Baseline Rd., and it numbered a tidy 17 individuals. The other drifted aimlessly about the indigenous plantings near The Shack; at one point, the birds went across the trail, and I quickly got on 13.  OMG THIS IS A PROOF OF THE GOLDBACH CONJECTURE!!!! As to the pics below, the male (by eye color) is from the flock at The Shack; the female (also by eye color) is from the flock that crossed Baseline Rd. Hilarious to watch as each one would get out of the way of traffic. By the way, the female is banded. How cool is that. Oak Thorne's handiwork, no doubt.  Two audio recordings, too, of the Bushtit vocalization that I believe functions as song. First is a series from a single individual (male by eye color); the second is a single bout of song that I pulled out of a longer recording of Black-capped Chickadees (pulled from MLML614320454).

Count is as exact as I could be. Large group foraging mid-level close to the road. Each individual I saw and counted were either black or brown-eared individuals (presumably the females of melanotis group). I did not note any birds belonging to the "interior" race. Likely more as Bushtits can be difficult to count, although I cannot confirm that all belonged to the melanotis group.   This was my first encounter with the "black-eared" ssp. Hesitant to list this as there are no records in eBird for the entirety of the United States.  From Mark Stackhouse regarding photos: Clearly in the melanotis group, and I’d guess that it would be P. m. dimorphicus, the expected subspecies for there. The next subspecies south (the one in this part of Mexico) is more brownish and less gray in the back than your birds. All the photos I have from this area are much more brownish/olive in the back.

Observation Details: Visiting feeder.  One of the males had distinct bluish coloration to its wing and tail feathers (see first two photos).  Reading Birds of the World, blue coloration is more characteristic of the interior subspecies (P. m. plumbeous) rather than the expected coastal PNW subspecies (P. m. saturatus).  It's hard to imagine any mixing between interior birds and north Olympic Peninsula birds, however.  Maybe it's just because of the way the light refracted through its feathers.

Observation Details: A flock bopped around the Greenlee/Waneka buffer for quite some time, then raided the Greenlee feeders. Flock size in such situations quite difficult to work out—despite lengthy period of observation (at least 20 minutes). When birds crossed the little clearings in the buffer and and at the feeder, I could get quickly on 20+, with at least 5 still hanging back. 25 likely an undercount.  Media:  ML612768147: typical adult female (by eye color). ML612768151: birds at millet feeder, and note band on one of the females (by eye color). ML612768156: part of the flock at suet feeder. ML612768161: part of the flock at millet feeder. ML612768166: The flock raids the Greenlee feeders. ML612768172: The flock at sundown in the Greenlee/Waneka buffer. Note the "Brownian motion," entirely typical. ML612768173: A single male (by eye color) feeding, with diverse vocalizations by flockmates.  Photo/video editing. Videos: slight stabilization for ML612768161 and ML612768173; wasn't necessary for ML612768172. For photos, the intense red/orange/yellow (higher wavelengths) is true/natural, given the low sun angle and surrounding vegetation; all images sharpened (because of low light conditions ).

Observation Details: The birds in this area are brown-crowned minimus group birds, P. m. californicus, which are paler and grayer than the coastal nominate P. m. minimus. I normally would not advocate using eBird subspecies groups, but these clearly are in the coastal group. I did not enter them to subspecies group in previous lists. By contrast, both coastal (aculeata) and interior (tenuissima) White-breasted Nuthatches are offered here (they do overlap or nearly so here in sw. Modoc Co.). The Bushtits are easily as distinct or more so, and putting them here reinforces the cismontane nature of the birds in the mixed oak and pine habitats here in sw. Modoc. Offering Bushtit with no subspecies groups is appropriate here to avoid leading on observers’ entries.

Observation Details: Photos were taken during my first brief birding outing on 11/5/23 at the Irvine Ranch Water District San Joaquin Marsh Wildlife Sanctuary. Photos were taken with a Canon 5D Mark II and Sigma 150-600 Contemporary lens. We met just before 10:00 with a few friends one of whom was a more avid birder who introduced me to the process and the apps eBird and Merlin. I did not use the apps until after I had processed the photos as my main goal was to take some photos initially on our brief 45 minute walk. I used Merlin to help ID the birds based on these photos and selected the species that best matched the photographs. I am not certain about the type of bird I observed as Merlin and eBird have different subtypes so took a best guess. I observed one Bushtit though movement suggested there were likely many more in the trees and bushes around the marsh.

Gathering nesting material, fluffy white bit in bill.— tried to take phone photos but couldn’t get close enough and then they disappeared.  — 100% certain, no doubt about it, brown caps on these BUSH.  — did manage to get better photos when did something I rarely do: I played tape for them. They responded aggressively to the “California” tape on Larkwire, which is prob Pacific form. They didn’t respond to the first “Oregon” tape I played. Managed to get some photos by doing this.   CKJ: Pacific type BUSH at Wickiup !!!!  Or, maybe? Observation Details: Count is as exact as I could be. Large group foraging mid-level close to the road. Each individual I saw and counted were either black or brown-eared individuals (presumably the females of melanotis group). I did not note any birds belonging to the "interior" race. Likely more as Bushtits can be difficult to count, although I cannot confirm that all belonged to the melanotis group.   This was my first encounter with the "black-eared" ssp. Hesitant to list this as there are no records in eBird for the entirety of the United States.  From Mark Stackhouse regarding photos: Clearly in the melanotis group, and I’d guess that it would be P. m. dimorphicus, the expected subspecies for there. The next subspecies south (the one in this part of Mexico) is more brownish and less gray in the back than your birds. All the photos I have from this area are much more brownish/olive in the back.

A male Downy Woodpecker helped out too. I'm guessing that all the birds I've attracted to my yard is why this tree didn't have an aphid infestation last year for the first time ever. More Bushtits please!!

It's hard to imagine any mixing between interior birds and north Olympic Peninsula birds, however.  Maybe it's just because of the way the light refracted through its feathers.

Locality: 1601 South Marion Street, Denver, CO US
Observation Details: Took turns between bushes and suet feeder (each got one turn at suet). Then one (clearly male due to all black eye, also had rounder fluffier body) stood still in bush and chirped / sang on outer branches for 3 minutes, flashing tail back and forth while female watched closely (probable mating display). Chirps and movement became more flurried toward end and female was hopping actively. She then flew off, followed by male a few seconds later. Bushtits did not approach water although it was within 3ft of their mating display, clearly visible and audible. In photo: Female watching and waiting for her turn at the suet feeder.
